08081nam a22011775i 9781501504266DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2018046517  a97815015042667 a10.1515/97815015042662doi  a(DE-B1597)463079  a(OCoLC)1055570217  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE10aP295 4aP295 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a415.01/82200aFreezing :bTheoretical Approaches and Empirical Domains /ced. by Jutta Hartmann, Marion Jäger, Andreas Konietzko, Susanne Winkler, Andreas Kehl. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VIII, 456 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Generative Grammar [SGG] ,x0167-4331 ;v13000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tExploring the concepts of Freezing: Theoretical and empirical perspectives -- tPart I: Theoretical advancement -- tCriterial Freezing in small clauses and the cartography of copular constructions -- tFreezing Effects in a free-Merge System -- tFreezing in complex prefields -- tPart II: Empirical domains -- tThe Freezing points of the (Dutch) adjectival system -- tFreezing in it-clefts: Movement and focus -- tCriterial Freezing in the syntax of particles -- tOnly syntax -- tFreezing and phi-feature agreement: On the role of [PERSON] -- tFreezing, Topic Opacity and Phase-based Cyclicity in Subject Islands -- tPart III: Interface extensions -- tFreezing: Between grammar and processing -- tHeavy NP shift in context: On the interaction of information structure and subextraction from shifted constituents -- tFreezing as a probabilistic phenomenon -- tAn experimental study on freezing and topicalization in English -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDisplacement is a fundamental property of human language, and the restrictions on displacement have been a central concern in generative grammar ever since Ross' (1967) ground-breaking observations of island constraints. While island phenomena have been investigated in detail from various perspectives, a different domain, the domain of Freezing, originally defined in terms of non-base structures, has received far less attention. This volume brings together papers that address the questions of: What are the different concepts of Freezing? Which empirical domains can they explain? Is Freezing a core-syntactic restriction or does information structure, or processing play a role? The collection of papers provides insights into the empirical basis of the Freezing Principle in relation to other restrictions on extraction in order to contribute to a broader understanding of the nature of restrictions on displacement in language. The overall goal of the volume is a reconsideration of Freezing and other (sub-)extraction phenomena, both from a theoretical and empirical perspective, by bringing together contributions from experts in the field to discuss and broaden our knowledge of the empirical range of Freezing phenomena as well as their explanation.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxWord order. 4aFreezing. 4aGenerative Grammatik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aDisplacement Restrictions.  aFreezing.  aLong-Distance Dependencies.1 aBayer, Josef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaves, Rui P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorver, Norbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCulicover, Peter W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallego, Ángel J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartma